<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Emissaries Return After Meeting With 'Arafat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0703160594 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1500 GMT 7 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0703160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Two Israeli emissaries returned home from Cairo 
after conferring there with PLO leaders, including Yasir 
'Arafat. They reported to the prime minister on the talks. Our 
political correspondent Shlomo Raz reports that the two, the 
prime minister's political adviser Jacques Neriya, and Colonel 
'Amos Gil'ad, Mr. Rabin's deputy military secretary, left for 
Cairo this morning after consultations with the prime minister. 
They were instructed to find out 'Arafat's real stand on the 
possible resumption of the talks between Israel and the PLO. 
  The PLO's ambassador in Cairo said an Israeli envoy would 
arrive in Tunis within two days to hand 'Arafat Israel's 
response to the organization's demands on the security of the 
Palestinians in the territories. He said the PLO would decide 
whether to renew the peace talks based on Israel's answers. 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 1400 GMT on 7 March 
reports that "Nabil Sha'th, head of the Palestinian delegation, 
told the PLO in Tunis that the Neriya-'Arafat meeting was 
positive, and that Neriya took notes, which he will deliver to 
Prime Minister Rabin this evening. Speaking to our 
correspondent, Sha'th said that it is still too early to speak 
of a summit meeting between 'Arafat and Rabin, but stressed that 
the contacts are positive, and that it is possible that 
developments will take place in several days, if Israel accepts 
the requests raised in Neriya's meeting with 'Arafat."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

