<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   European Union Delegation in Damascus for Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Paper Comments on Talks </H4>
<F P=102> JN0703085194 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0545 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0703085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] TISHRIN comments on the visit of the European Unity 
delegation to Damascus and President Hafiz al-Asad's emphasis, 
during his reception of the delegation, of Syria's support for 
the peace process despite doubts about Israeli seriousness on 
this process. 
  TISHRIN says: Welcoming any European or international effort 
to activate the peace process, we reaffirm that peace is a 
collective interest, and that the conditions and bases of peace 
must be responded to in a positive and constructive spirit. The 
paper notes that Europe has come to realize that peace cannot be 
achieved under the continued Israeli occupation and that partial 
agreements and separate deals cannot lead to lasting peace. 
Europe has also come to realize that no peace is possible under 
the continued Israeli terrorism, massacres, and crimes. 
  TISHRIN says: Undoubtedly, when it denounces all those 
Israeli anti-peace practices, Europe stresses its demands and 
calls for the establishment of a just, comprehensive peace. 
Naturally, these demands and denunciations of Israeli practices 
should be linked to practical stands and measures leading to an 
active and effective European role to help Arabs restore their 
rights and territories and to halt the Israeli massacres. 
  Concluding its editorial, TISHRIN says: Europe should move 
to assume its political responsibilities toward the situation in 
the region, including the issue of a just, comprehensive peace, 
and the enforcement of the resolutions of the international 
legitimacy, which primarily call for Israel's full withdrawal 
from the occupied Arab territories. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

