<F P=103> LD0803123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, March, 8, IRNA -- The Foreign Ministry 
Tuesday strongly denied a claim by Egyptian President Hosni 
Mubarak that Iran was involved in an attempt on the life of 
Egyptian Premier, 'Atif Sidqi. 
  Foreign Ministry Spokesman, Morteza Sarmadi, told IRNA that 
such baseless and false allegations indicated not only the 
"Cairo regime's helplessness and confusion but also the critical 
situation in that country." 
  Sarmadi expressed "deep regret" that a person at the head of 
state level raised "such false claims based on fabrications" 
against the Islamic Republic of Iran. 
  In an interview published in the latest issue of Kuwaiti 
daily, AL-QABAS, Mubarak accused Iran of paying dlrs 13,000 to 
an Egyptian terrorist to assassinate the Egyptain prime 
minister. 

