<F P=101> Israel </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Returns From Cairo, Discusses 'Arafat Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0803144294 Tel Aviv MA'ARIV in Hebrew 8 Mar 94 p 5--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> TA0803144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv MA'ARIV </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hemi Shalev, Alex Fishman, 'Oded Granot, and </F>
Shefi Gabay] 
  [Excerpt] Jacques Neriya, the prime minister's political 
adviser, spent four hours in Cairo yesterday meeting with 
'Arafat and brought back a pessimistic message. Political 
sources in Jerusalem estimated that chances are nil for an 
imminent meeting between Rabin and 'Arafat. 
  Yasir 'Arafat and Yitzhaq Rabin spoke on the phone on 
Sunday. 
They discussed the possibility of holding a summit meeting but 
decided there would be no sense in such a meeting if it is not 
certain to result in an agreement. 
  Yesterday's meeting in Cairo was attended by Colonel 'Amos 
Gil'ad, Rabin's aide-de-camp, and Israeli Ambassador to Egypt 
David Sultan. The PLO leader spelled out his conditions for the 
resumption of the negotiations: banning gun-toting settlers 
from moving around towns in the territories, relocating the 
settlers from the heart of Hebron to Qiryat Arba', and 
stationing an international force in the territories. 
  'Arafat surprised his audience with additional demands which 
totally ignore the Cairo agreement. Among other things, he is 
demanding that the size of the autonomous area in Jericho be 
doubled, that Palestinian policemen be stationed at the Jordan 
River bridges, and other demands that gave rise to disputes in 
the past. 
  Neriya gave 'Arafat a message from Rabin saying that Israel 
is willing to significantly accelerate the negotiations and the 
implementation of the agreement once it is signed. 
  'Arafat departed for Tunis after meeting with Neriya. 
"Neriya promised everything would be all right, but he made no 
promises beyond the resolutions passed by the Israeli Government 
in the aftermath of the massacre in Hebron," a senior 
Palestinian source told MA'ARIV last night. 
  Palestinian sources noted that both 'Arafat and Neriya 
voiced 
their apprehension that the peace process might be blown to 
smithereens. "What the settler did in the Cave of the 
Patriarchs was to massacre the peace process," 'Arafat said. He 
asked that Israel investigate the role of the Israel Defense 
Forces in the event. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

