<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sources: PLO Insists on UN Hebron Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0803173594 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 8 Mar 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> PM0803173594 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Muhammad 'Allam: "Washington Proposes, PLO Rules </F>
Out Imminent Meeting Between 'Arafat, Rabin"] 
  [Excerpts] Cairo -- [Passage omitted] Palestinian sources 
have said that "'Arafat will not meet with Israeli Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres until the Security Council adopts a clear 
and decisive resolution" on the Hebron incident. 
  The sources said that U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher offered Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political adviser to the 
Palestinian president, during the latter's visit to Washington 
the U.S. Administration's willingness to host a high-level 
meeting in Washington to discuss Palestinian demands, resume the 
negotiations, and impart impetus to the implementation of the 
Gaza-Jericho agreement, because that "would be considered an 
achievement and a victory over the forces of extremism." 
  The Palestinian sources stressed "Palestinian eagerness to 
continue the negotiations and implement the agreement." 
However, they expressed the "PLO's insistence on the adoption 
of an international resolution, inasmuch as Security Council 
resolutions should not be ignored as an authority, nor should 
this disregard be perpetuated, as reflected in the U.S. offer." 
The sources stressed that the "PLO cannot ignore angry 
Palestinian reactions inside the the occupied territories." 
  The sources said that "a meeting between 'Arafat and Rabin 
in 
this atmosphere will not be successful." However, they pointed 
out that "the U.S. position is being studied, as is the 
possibility of holding such a meeting" -- that is, if suitable 
conditions are available to ensure its success, "first and 
foremost the adoption of an international resolution." The 
sources went on: "It is the U.S. Administration which is in an 
embarrassing position, not the PLO, which enjoys collective 
international -- with the exception of the United States and 
Israel -- support for its demands." [passage omitted] 
  Asked whether the PLO would accept Israeli proposals that 
respond to PLO demands, provided an international resolution is 
not adopted, the Palestinian sources stressed to AL-HAYAH that 
"that is ruled out, because it would constitute a precedent." 
They also said: "The international organization's disregard 
for a massacre committed within the context of a conflict on 
which a considerable number of international resolutions have 
been adopted is a precedent with regard to the Security Council 
and represents the first real nail in the United Nation's 
coffin." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13081 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes046dd_94006" </HT>


