<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-al-Shafi Urges PLO To Stand Firm on Demands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0803154194 Jerusalem AL-QUDS in Arabic 8 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> TA0803154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-QUDS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jerusalem -- Dr. Haydar 'Abd-al-Shafi has 
emphasized that the peace process has lost much of its 
credibility in the wake of the Hebron massacre. This situation 
has also impacted on the Palestinian leadership, which has lost 
a significant part of its credibility as a result of Israel's 
practices on the ground. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi noted that after the massacre, the 
Palestinian popular mood lost confidence in the current 
political process. It believes that the talks will be futile 
and harmful if they are resumed without Israel dropping its 
claims on Jerusalem and the settlements and halting all 
settlement activities, which seek to create new facts that 
dictate the outlines of the final stage before the beginning of 
the interim stage. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi stressed that the Palestinian leadership, 
which wants to be apprised of what the people in the occupied 
territories are saying now, should insist on the terms it has 
set and not back down. If the leadership wishes to regain its 
credibility, it should make those terms preconditions for 
returning to the negotiating table. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi added: We are not demanding impossible 
conditions, because the issue of the Palestinian residents' 
security must be sacred to the decisionmakers. Therefore, we 
must adhere to our demands, epitomized by disarming the 
settlers; ensuring effective international protection for our 
people in the occupied territories; and evacuating the 
settlements from Arab towns and heavily populated areas, such as 
the settlement quarter in the heart of Hebron and similar places. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi pointed out that adherence to these 
conditions might lead to the derailment of the peace process but 
that should this happen, the issue must be referred back to the 
international community to be resolved by it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

