<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Rabin-'Arafat Talk </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0903072894 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 0600 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0903072894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Udi Segal] </F>
  [Text] The resolution about to be endorsed by the UN 
Security Council is one the PLO has been anticipating. The 
issue of Jerusalem -- namely, the clause which applies the 
Geneva Convention to the territories, including Jerusalem -- is 
the most crucial article of that resolution. Israel objects to 
the clause, but it is expected to be endorsed nevertheless, 
since the United States will probably abstain on this clause, 
rather than veto it. 
  The resolution denouncing the Hebron massacre, which the 
Security Council will debate tonight, will pave the way for 
renewing the negotiations. Political sources in Jerusalem have 
said that the clause incorporating Jerusalem in the territories 
is an achievement for the Palestinians, and within a few days, 
it will pave the way to direct contacts toward the resumption of 
negotiations. The contacts will address the steps Israel is to 
take in the wake of the Hebron massacre to secure the PLO return 
to the negotiations. 
  For Israel, the Jerusalem clause is disagreeable, but it is 
neither new nor very significant. It is disagreeable, but not 
tragic, Foreign Ministry sources said. 
  Last night, Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin held his second 
telephone conversation with Yasir 'Arafat in two days. Rabin 
told 'Arafat that Israel will not accept all the demands 'Arafat 
had conveyed to political adviser Jacques Neriya as a condition 
for resuming the negotiations. Rabin urged 'Arafat to return to 
the negotiating table. 'Arafat replied: Not yet. It is 
believed that after the UN Security Council passes a denouncing 
resolution, a senior-level meeting -- probably between Peres and 
Mahmud 'Abbas, possibly between Rabin and 'Arafat -- will be 
held within a few days, heralding the delegations' return to 
intensive talks on the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho 
agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13098 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes046yy_94004" </HT>


