<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Saudi Arabia </F>
<H3> <TI>   King Husayn Performs Pilgrimage, Meets With Fahd </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0903111094 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 9 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0903111094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sulayman Nimr: "King Husayn Performs Minor </F>
Pilgrimage, Holds Talks With King Fahd"] 
  [Text] Jeddah -- King Husayn yesterday evening performed 
minor pilgrimage rituals in holy Mecca. He had arrived in 
Jeddah at midday in his first visit to the Kingdom of Saudi 
Arabia since the Gulf crisis erupted in the summer of 1990. 
King Husayn used to visit holy Mecca to perform minor 
pilgrimage on al-Qadr night, 27 Ramadan, every year, and to 
visit the tomb of the great prophet. But he could not do that 
for over three and a half years because of the Gulf crisis. 
  King Fahd Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz received the Jordanian monarch 
late last night in holy Mecca, where the custodian of the two 
holy mosques is spending the last 10 days of Ramadan close to 
the Kaaba. 
  The meeting between the Saudi and Jordanian monarchs is the 
first between the two leaders, who were separated by their 
positions during the crisis of the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. 
Riyadh considered Jordan's position substantially supportive of 
Iraqi President Saddam Husayn. What further aggravated the 
crisis in relations between the countries -- which is happening 
for the first time -- was the position of the Jordanian media 
and press toward Saudi Arabia during and after the crisis. 
  Arab diplomatic circles hope that the expected meeting 
[al-liqa' al-mutawaqqa'] between the custodian of the two holy 
mosques and the Jordanian monarch will lead to opening a new 
page in inter-Arab relations based on sound and clear 
foundations. The circles said that there is a positive 
atmosphere with the king vis-a-vis the gradual restoration to 
health [of relations] with the Arab states which adopted 
positions that disappointed the Saudis during the Gulf crisis. 
In this connection the circles cited the custodian of the two 
holy mosques' meeting over a month ago with Palestinian 
President Yasir 'Arafat, who visited Saudi Arabia to perform 
minor pilgrimage. He was received by King Fahd in Riyadh. The 
sources also cited the continued normalization of Saudi-Yemeni 
relations, which culminated last month in the Saudi monarch's 
reception of 'Ali Salim al-Bid, deputy chairman of the Yemeni 
Presidential Council. 
  It was noted that King Husayn and the delegation 
accompanying 
him -- which included al-Sharif Zayd Bin-Shakir, head of the 
Royal Court, and some members of the ruling Jordanian family -- 
were accorded a reception usually accorded to Arab and Islamic 
leaders who arrive in the Kingdom to perform minor pilgrimage. 
The king and the delegation were received at King 'Abd-al-'Aziz 
Airport in Jeddah by Prince Majid Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz, the amir of 
the holy Mecca region. And King Husayn stayed at al-Hamra' 
Palace. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

