<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Efforts of PRC, Iran Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0903161894 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0903161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] China and Iran have asked Islamabad to defer voting 
on the human rights resolution on Kashmir in Geneva. This was 
announced by the Pakistan foreign minister, Sardar Asif Ahmad 
Ali, at Islamabad a short while ago. He told a press conference 
that consequently Pakistan has authorized China and Iran to 
decide the best course they feel is available for it. 
  Earlier, Beijing and Tehran approached Islamabad to postpone 
for three hours the voting on the resolution this evening so 
that further consultation could be held on certain proposals 
made by them. These options included either withdrawal of the 
resolution or its indefinite deferment. PTI, quoting observers 
in Islamabad, says Pakistan can agree to withdraw the resolution. 

</TEXT>

