<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Broadcasts To Urge Toppling of Regime </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1003093894 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 0600 GMT 10 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1003093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Cairo, Libyan opposition figure Muhammad Fayiz 
Jibril said that next week the Libyan opposition will begin 
radio broadcasts from a Middle Eastern country, which he did not 
identify. Jibril said the radio will urge Libyans to escalate 
the struggle to topple al-Qadhdhafi and set up a democracy in 
Libya. He appealed to concerned international organizations to 
rescue the life of Colonel (Muftah Qurdum), a Libyan opposition 
figure whom the Libyan Television presented on Monday [7 March] 
as a spy working for the United States. 
  Qurdum introduced himself as a former Army colonel. He 
admitted that while residing in Switzerland he contacted Libyans 
living abroad, who supplied the Americans with information. He 
added that the Americans sought information on the Libyan Armed 
Forces and the Libyan missile program. They were planning to 
attack Libya with the help of their spies, who would then seize 
power. 
  Muhammad Fayiz Jibril said Qurdum made these false 
confessions under duress. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

