<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   YSP Proposes Two Options for Resolving Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0803170394 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 8 Mar 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM0803170394 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Abdallah Hammudah: "Socialist Party Rejects </F>
Federation and Offers One of Two Options: Document or Partition"] 
  [Excerpt] London -- Yemeni sources have emphasized that the 
current position of the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] on ways of 
resolving the political crisis threatening the unity of the two 
parts of Yemen can be summed up in two options. The first is 
that the General People's Congress [GPC] and the Yemeni Reform 
Grouping [YRG], the two northern partners in the ruling 
coalition, implement the Pledge and Accord Document in 
accordance with the interpretation and the measures agreed on by 
the YSP and the opposition, regarding which the GPC and the YRG 
still have some reservations or objections; or, that there be a 
return to the situation obtaining prior to 22 May 1990 and an 
announcement of the end of the unity experiment. 
  The sources said that Brigadier General Mujahid 
Abu-Shawarib, 
deputy prime minister for internal affairs and member of the 
Political Forces' Dialogue Committee, which drafted the Pledge 
and Accord Document, late last month offered the YSP leadership 
the federation option as a way out of the crisis, along the same 
lines suggested last October by Salim Salih Muhammad, YSP 
assistant secretary general and Presidential Council member, but 
the party's Political Bureau rejected that option on the grounds 
that that suggestion had been overtaken by the recent military 
confrontations in Abyan and H rft Sufyan. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

