<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pro-Saddam Kurdish Officials Reaffirm Loyalty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0903170794 Baghdad Republic of Iraq Radio Network in 
Arabic 1530 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0903170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad Republic of Iraq Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baha'-al-Din Ahmad, speaker of the Legislative 
Council of the Kurdistan Autonomous Region, and Ja'far 
'Abd-al-Karim al-Barzanji, chairman of the Executive Council of 
the Kurdistan Autonomous Region, have commended the great and 
prominent role leader President Saddam Husayn, the architect of 
autonomy, has played in reaching a just and peaceful settlement 
of the Kurdish issue on democratic and fair terms on the basis 
of the doctrine, creed, and principles upheld by the Arab 
Socialist Ba'th Party. 
  In statements to the IRAQI NEWS AGENCY on the 24th 
anniversary of the issuance of the historic 11 March statement, 
the two Kurdish officials added that settling the Kurdish issue 
and halting infighting in the Kurdistan region were only some of 
the significant accomplishments of the glorious 17-30 July 
revolution. They reiterated the Kurds' allegiance to the 
historic and unique leadership of leader President Saddam 
Husayn. They also reaffirmed their willingness to make 
sacrifices to safeguard Iraq's unity and thwart the enemies' 
schemes, which aim to undermine Iraq's sovereignty and national 
unity. 
  The two Kurdish officials noted that the lawlessness, 
instability, insecurity, anarchy, murders, and thefts currently 
prevailing in the Kurdistan region are cogent proof of the false 
claims made by archtraitors and archagents, who have accepted 
subservience to their foreign masters, the enemies of Iraq. 
  Concluding their statements, they asserted that agents and 
traitors will be defeated, with God's help and the determination 
of zealous Kurds, particularly since the zealous Kurds have 
always demonstrated their support for the courageous leadership 
of leader President Saddam Husayn. 

</TEXT>

