<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Three Replaced in `Kurdish Government' Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0903122694 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 8 Mar 94 p4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0903122694 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Adnan Husayn: "`Kurdish Government' Reshuffle </F>
Affecting Three of Talabani's Ministers"] 
  [Excerpts] London -- AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned that 
the "government of the region of Kurdistan" which runs the 
affairs of the Kurdish areas in northern Iraq has reshuffled its 
portfolios and that three ministries held by members of the 
leadership of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan [PUK], led by 
Jalal Talabani, were affected. 
  Iraqi Kurdish sources told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT yesterday that 
Sa'di Ahmad Birah, the agriculture minister in the Kurdish 
Government, replaced Humanitarian Affairs "Minister" Muhammad 
Tawfiq Rahim, who left the government; that the agriculture 
"ministry" portfolio was given to PUK Executive Committee Member 
Hazim Yusufi; and that Jamal 'Abdul, former governor of 
al-Sulaymaniyah, replaced Shirku Biks, the former "minister" and 
well-known poet who resigned in December last year, as culture 
"minister." [passage omitted] 
  PUK sources have confirmed the cabinet reshuffle but denied 
that it had any political significance. [passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile, some Iraqi opposition figures and groups living 
in 
the British capital have completed preparations for a week of 
solidarity with the Iraqi people next week with the 
participation of influential figures in the fields of politics, 
culture, and art. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

