<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Weapons Found in PFLP Leader's Car on Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0803210694 Amman AL-BILAD in Arabic 9 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN0803210694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-BILAD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Let us begin [Secretary General of the Democratic 
Front for the Liberation of Palestine] Nayif Hawatimah's story 
where that of the secretary general of another front ends. 
  During his visit [to Jordan] where he met with the prime 
minister, Nayif Hawatimah expressed displeasure with the 
meticulous search of his car. 
  Prime Minister al-Majali explained to Nayif Hawatimah that 
he 
was not personally targeted by this search but that the 
Jordanian security authorities at the border posts have started 
to carefully search all incoming vehicles to Jordan, whether 
private or official. 
  Al-Majali explained to Hawatimah that Jordan was forced to 
do 
this out of its fear that these vehicles might be used to 
transport weapons into Jordan as had taken place with the car of 
George Habash [the secretary general of the Popular Front the 
Liberation of Palestine, PFLP]. 
  The Jordanian version says that during Habash's recent visit 
to Jordan, his car was searched and various types of weapons and 
silencers were found in it. 
  On the other hand, the security forces have stepped up their 
surveillance of all the Jordanian border posts to foil any arms 
smuggling operation, particularly after the two cinema 
explosions. 

</TEXT>

